WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.970 align:middle line:90%


00:00:02.970 --> 00:00:06.435 align:middle line:90%
[WAVES CRASHING]

00:00:06.435 --> 00:00:46.165 align:middle line:90%


00:00:46.165 --> 00:00:47.790 align:middle line:84%
>> This is not a
place where I grew up.

00:00:47.790 --> 00:00:50.340 align:middle line:90%


00:00:50.340 --> 00:00:51.990 align:middle line:90%
I did not inherit this house.

00:00:51.990 --> 00:00:52.908 align:middle line:90%
I built this house.

00:00:52.908 --> 00:00:53.950 align:middle line:90%
>> You built it yourself?

00:00:53.950 --> 00:00:54.180 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:00:54.180 --> 00:00:54.980 align:middle line:90%
Mm-hmm.

00:00:54.980 --> 00:00:56.430 align:middle line:90%
>> Looks amazing, by the way.

00:00:56.430 --> 00:00:57.780 align:middle line:90%
We hope you can show it to us.

00:00:57.780 --> 00:00:58.140 align:middle line:90%
>> Oh, yeah.

00:00:58.140 --> 00:00:58.940 align:middle line:90%
>> Cool.

00:00:58.940 --> 00:01:00.875 align:middle line:90%
>> You can look at it.

00:01:00.875 --> 00:01:03.000 align:middle line:84%
I mean, this is just what
I built in my spare time.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:07.893 align:middle line:84%
And it's an architectural
monstrosity, but it's mine.

00:01:07.893 --> 00:01:09.060 align:middle line:90%
I don't owe any money on it.

00:01:09.060 --> 00:01:11.700 align:middle line:90%


00:01:11.700 --> 00:01:13.380 align:middle line:90%
It's where I live.

00:01:13.380 --> 00:01:16.260 align:middle line:84%
>> How did you come
up with the design?

00:01:16.260 --> 00:01:19.620 align:middle line:84%
>> I didn't-- doesn't
have a design.

00:01:19.620 --> 00:01:21.220 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, I poured the foundation.

00:01:21.220 --> 00:01:22.070 align:middle line:90%
I milled the wood.

00:01:22.070 --> 00:01:23.093 align:middle line:90%
I cut down the trees.

00:01:23.093 --> 00:01:24.510 align:middle line:84%
I trucked the wood
here and there.

00:01:24.510 --> 00:01:26.970 align:middle line:90%
I nailed the boards up.

00:01:26.970 --> 00:01:32.130 align:middle line:84%
But never-- no construction crew
has ever worked on this house.

00:01:32.130 --> 00:01:34.810 align:middle line:84%
People are, what's it
like to live off-the-grid?

00:01:34.810 --> 00:01:36.070 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:01:36.070 --> 00:01:36.870 align:middle line:90%
I'm just living.

00:01:36.870 --> 00:01:37.745 align:middle line:90%
This is where I live.

00:01:37.745 --> 00:01:41.053 align:middle line:90%


00:01:41.053 --> 00:01:44.546 align:middle line:90%
[WAVES CRASHING]

00:01:44.546 --> 00:01:47.540 align:middle line:90%


00:01:47.540 --> 00:01:51.033 align:middle line:90%
[RUNNING WATER]

00:01:51.033 --> 00:01:57.540 align:middle line:90%


00:01:57.540 --> 00:02:00.000 align:middle line:84%
>> On Lasqueti Island, and
when you're off-the-grid,

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:03.540 align:middle line:84%
we spend our time dealing
with the three things that you

00:02:03.540 --> 00:02:06.780 align:middle line:84%
people in the city spend
the least time with.

00:02:06.780 --> 00:02:10.419 align:middle line:10%
And that's heat,
light, and water.

00:02:10.419 --> 00:02:12.010 align:middle line:10%
When your water goes
down, your water

00:02:12.010 --> 00:02:16.580 align:middle line:10%
doesn't come out of your tap,
you call up somebody and bitch.

00:02:16.580 --> 00:02:18.200 align:middle line:84%
When your electricity
doesn't work,

00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:19.530 align:middle line:90%
you call up somebody and bitch.

00:02:19.530 --> 00:02:21.530 align:middle line:84%
Well, around here, if
your water doesn't go out,

00:02:21.530 --> 00:02:22.370 align:middle line:90%
you think, oh, god.

00:02:22.370 --> 00:02:25.110 align:middle line:90%
The hose is broken or something.

00:02:25.110 --> 00:02:29.200 align:middle line:84%
And you go out there and find it
before your water drains away.

00:02:29.200 --> 00:02:32.680 align:middle line:84%
After all the Y2K
panic, every community

00:02:32.680 --> 00:02:35.330 align:middle line:84%
had to have a disaster
management plan.

00:02:35.330 --> 00:02:38.620 align:middle line:84%
They sent over a woman
from the regional district.

00:02:38.620 --> 00:02:40.360 align:middle line:10%
So she starts off
and she says, OK.

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:44.620 align:middle line:84%
She says, what are you going
to do when your power goes out?

00:02:44.620 --> 00:02:48.700 align:middle line:84%
And I said, well, my power
is not going to go out.

00:02:48.700 --> 00:02:50.560 align:middle line:84%
She said, well, how
can you be so sure?

00:02:50.560 --> 00:02:52.970 align:middle line:84%
And I said, well,
I make it myself.

00:02:52.970 --> 00:02:55.720 align:middle line:84%
I have solar panels
and a water wheel.

00:02:55.720 --> 00:02:59.170 align:middle line:84%
And because of what I'm doing,
I have three generators.

00:02:59.170 --> 00:03:02.170 align:middle line:84%
But basically, if my
power goes out, I fix it.

00:03:02.170 --> 00:03:04.720 align:middle line:10%
>> We've done a lot to have
a convenient lifestyle.

00:03:04.720 --> 00:03:08.770 align:middle line:10%
But it's a lifestyle that we
have really built up and made

00:03:08.770 --> 00:03:09.780 align:middle line:10%
for ourselves.

00:03:09.780 --> 00:03:11.780 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I just like it
when I turn on the water,

00:03:11.780 --> 00:03:14.710 align:middle line:84%
I know exactly where the
water is coming from.

00:03:14.710 --> 00:03:17.480 align:middle line:84%
I know when the washing
machine is draining,

00:03:17.480 --> 00:03:19.990 align:middle line:84%
I know where that
water's going to.

00:03:19.990 --> 00:03:22.520 align:middle line:84%
And I know when I
flick the light switch,

00:03:22.520 --> 00:03:24.550 align:middle line:84%
I know where that
electricity came from.

00:03:24.550 --> 00:03:29.300 align:middle line:84%
I can account for it all
within a very small area.

00:03:29.300 --> 00:03:33.420 align:middle line:84%
>> I grew up on boats and
in the bush, all right?

00:03:33.420 --> 00:03:35.570 align:middle line:84%
And one of my favorite
sounds is silence.

00:03:35.570 --> 00:03:39.630 align:middle line:90%


00:03:39.630 --> 00:03:42.720 align:middle line:10%
>> I mean, I lived off-the-grid
for most of my life,

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:46.590 align:middle line:10%
until I was about 28 or 29.

00:03:46.590 --> 00:03:50.100 align:middle line:84%
I had a cell phone for six
months, and I hated it.

00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:51.030 align:middle line:90%
It was terrible.

00:03:51.030 --> 00:03:52.730 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I went from
having no phone

00:03:52.730 --> 00:03:55.230 align:middle line:84%
to having a cell phone where
people can call you when you're

00:03:55.230 --> 00:03:57.000 align:middle line:90%
out walking in the woods.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:03:59.437 align:middle line:84%
I don't want to be called
while I'm walking in the woods.

00:03:59.437 --> 00:04:02.150 align:middle line:90%
[CHUCKLE]

00:04:02.150 --> 00:04:07.080 align:middle line:90%
>> I have very similar fears.

00:04:07.080 --> 00:04:11.310 align:middle line:10%
I don't know where to start
to become self-reliant.

00:04:11.310 --> 00:04:14.610 align:middle line:10%
So I think that's a problem,
because I have grown up

00:04:14.610 --> 00:04:16.950 align:middle line:10%
as part of a generation that
just flicks on a switch.

00:04:16.950 --> 00:04:18.035 align:middle line:10%
>> Absolutely.

00:04:18.035 --> 00:04:19.410 align:middle line:10%
That's part of
why I'm doing what

00:04:19.410 --> 00:04:22.810 align:middle line:10%
I'm doing, is to create a place
where my daughter can survive,

00:04:22.810 --> 00:04:24.560 align:middle line:10%
really.

00:04:24.560 --> 00:04:27.580 align:middle line:10%
I don't want to sound
like a doomsday person,

00:04:27.580 --> 00:04:30.720 align:middle line:10%
but how we're virtually
converting the biosphere

00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:36.390 align:middle line:10%
into a human sphere,
it's just not

00:04:36.390 --> 00:04:39.900 align:middle line:10%
possible to sustain
what we're doing at all.

00:04:39.900 --> 00:04:43.990 align:middle line:84%
And this is one of the last
frontiers, if you will,

00:04:43.990 --> 00:04:47.550 align:middle line:84%
of where civilization hasn't
come and fundamentally chopped

00:04:47.550 --> 00:04:50.550 align:middle line:84%
everything down and
created human plantations.

00:04:50.550 --> 00:04:56.660 align:middle line:90%


00:04:56.660 --> 00:05:02.720 align:middle line:10%
>> I think there's a
portion of the population,

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:09.020 align:middle line:10%
probably mostly older, who find
it more challenging to live

00:05:09.020 --> 00:05:13.910 align:middle line:10%
here, that would like nothing
better than to have a power

00:05:13.910 --> 00:05:17.360 align:middle line:10%
meter and all the power they
need for electric heat and not

00:05:17.360 --> 00:05:20.120 align:middle line:10%
have to haul firewood in.

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:24.230 align:middle line:84%
I think in general, most of
the people that live here

00:05:24.230 --> 00:05:27.320 align:middle line:84%
would not wish to
connect to hydro.

00:05:27.320 --> 00:05:30.313 align:middle line:10%
>> In the '70s, Lasqueti
turned down hydro.

00:05:30.313 --> 00:05:32.230 align:middle line:84%
They didn't want to give
Lasqueti electricity.

00:05:32.230 --> 00:05:34.910 align:middle line:84%
They wanted to use Lasqueti as
a jumping-- as a stepping stone

00:05:34.910 --> 00:05:36.590 align:middle line:84%
to get electricity
from the mainland

00:05:36.590 --> 00:05:37.910 align:middle line:90%
over to Vancouver Island.

00:05:37.910 --> 00:05:40.530 align:middle line:84%
I think it was more of
an anti-establishment,

00:05:40.530 --> 00:05:42.980 align:middle line:84%
anti-corporation
kind of mindset.

00:05:42.980 --> 00:05:48.650 align:middle line:84%
In the '80s, solar,
wind, and micro-hydro

00:05:48.650 --> 00:05:51.320 align:middle line:90%
became viable options.

00:05:51.320 --> 00:05:56.810 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of people got really
into alternative energy stuff.

00:05:56.810 --> 00:06:02.330 align:middle line:84%
So when people realized that
they could have electricity

00:06:02.330 --> 00:06:04.608 align:middle line:84%
without running
a generator, they

00:06:04.608 --> 00:06:05.900 align:middle line:90%
were pretty excited about that.

00:06:05.900 --> 00:06:09.093 align:middle line:90%


00:06:09.093 --> 00:06:10.510 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the reality
of Lasqueti is

00:06:10.510 --> 00:06:16.300 align:middle line:84%
that it's just not close enough
to any connected communities.

00:06:16.300 --> 00:06:20.200 align:middle line:84%
>> This place, as you probably
found just getting here,

00:06:20.200 --> 00:06:23.350 align:middle line:90%
is a pain.

00:06:23.350 --> 00:06:26.780 align:middle line:90%
It's not an easy place to live.

00:06:26.780 --> 00:06:29.080 align:middle line:90%
>> We don't want a car ferry.

00:06:29.080 --> 00:06:30.430 align:middle line:90%
>> Tell me why?

00:06:30.430 --> 00:06:33.010 align:middle line:90%
>> Because we know who's here.

00:06:33.010 --> 00:06:37.360 align:middle line:84%
>> The people that I know that
live here really like it being

00:06:37.360 --> 00:06:41.820 align:middle line:84%
different and that we're wanting
it to be difficult to live here

00:06:41.820 --> 00:06:48.040 align:middle line:84%
because we don't want folks
to come here and just change

00:06:48.040 --> 00:06:49.420 align:middle line:90%
the beauty that's here.

00:06:49.420 --> 00:06:52.150 align:middle line:84%
If you come here because you
love it here, then leave it.

00:06:52.150 --> 00:06:56.550 align:middle line:84%
And that's what I'm trying
to do in my impact--

00:06:56.550 --> 00:07:01.390 align:middle line:84%
is develop it in a way
that's sustainable for humans

00:07:01.390 --> 00:07:07.390 align:middle line:84%
but not going to
forever destroy it

00:07:07.390 --> 00:07:12.670 align:middle line:84%
ecologically for all the other
species that this is home to.

00:07:12.670 --> 00:07:15.250 align:middle line:84%
>> We have legislation on
Lasqueti that says one house

00:07:15.250 --> 00:07:17.030 align:middle line:90%
per 10 acres.

00:07:17.030 --> 00:07:21.010 align:middle line:84%
And we brought that
legislation in because we

00:07:21.010 --> 00:07:25.600 align:middle line:84%
felt that 10 acres was the
smallest sustainable parcel

00:07:25.600 --> 00:07:28.690 align:middle line:84%
of land a family could
live on for firewood,

00:07:28.690 --> 00:07:34.630 align:middle line:84%
for water, for the ability to
grow food and be sustainable.

00:07:34.630 --> 00:07:38.620 align:middle line:84%
The general attitude
of people that

00:07:38.620 --> 00:07:41.860 align:middle line:84%
will trouble themselves to
live in a place like this

00:07:41.860 --> 00:07:43.690 align:middle line:90%
is independence.

00:07:43.690 --> 00:07:48.070 align:middle line:84%
And most people you
will talk to, I think,

00:07:48.070 --> 00:07:52.470 align:middle line:84%
will tell you that part of the
allure of living on Lasqueti

00:07:52.470 --> 00:07:55.660 align:middle line:90%
for them is that it's off-grid.

00:07:55.660 --> 00:07:59.740 align:middle line:84%
And I think most of
us have a great deal

00:07:59.740 --> 00:08:02.800 align:middle line:90%
of fondness for that challenge.

00:08:02.800 --> 00:08:06.940 align:middle line:90%


00:08:06.940 --> 00:08:09.700 align:middle line:84%
>> It's not unusual to see
houses with solar panels,

00:08:09.700 --> 00:08:13.330 align:middle line:84%
farms with wind turbines,
people collecting rainwater.

00:08:13.330 --> 00:08:15.430 align:middle line:84%
Some have even
managed to disconnect

00:08:15.430 --> 00:08:17.350 align:middle line:84%
from those traditional
connections

00:08:17.350 --> 00:08:19.180 align:middle line:90%
by going off-the-grid.

00:08:19.180 --> 00:08:22.000 align:middle line:84%
That's something Dr. Phillip
Vannini is interested in.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:24.940 align:middle line:84%
He's the Canada research
chair in Innovative Learning

00:08:24.940 --> 00:08:27.250 align:middle line:84%
and Public Ethnography
at Royal Roads

00:08:27.250 --> 00:08:29.530 align:middle line:90%
University in Victoria BC.

00:08:29.530 --> 00:08:31.460 align:middle line:90%
And Dr. Vannini joins me now.

00:08:31.460 --> 00:08:34.000 align:middle line:84%
I think we all know
what off-the-grid means,

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:37.240 align:middle line:84%
but what does it mean for the
purposes of your research?

00:08:37.240 --> 00:08:39.760 align:middle line:84%
>> The government of Canada
actually defines off-the-grid

00:08:39.760 --> 00:08:44.020 align:middle line:84%
as being disconnected from
the electricity grid servicing

00:08:44.020 --> 00:08:45.920 align:middle line:90%
a particular region.

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:48.530 align:middle line:84%
So essentially, if you
produce your own electricity,

00:08:48.530 --> 00:08:49.960 align:middle line:90%
you're off-the-grid.

00:08:49.960 --> 00:08:54.380 align:middle line:10%
Now, we use that expression
in other contexts as well.

00:08:54.380 --> 00:08:56.350 align:middle line:84%
Now generally, people
that are self-sufficient

00:08:56.350 --> 00:08:59.290 align:middle line:84%
for their electricity
are also off other grids.

00:08:59.290 --> 00:09:01.865 align:middle line:10%
They may have their
own water supply.

00:09:01.865 --> 00:09:03.490 align:middle line:10%
They may take care
of their own garbage

00:09:03.490 --> 00:09:05.230 align:middle line:10%
rather than have pickup.

00:09:05.230 --> 00:09:08.440 align:middle line:10%
They may have no television, for
example, and things like that.

00:09:08.440 --> 00:09:10.717 align:middle line:10%
I'm interested in
this for two reasons.

00:09:10.717 --> 00:09:12.550 align:middle line:10%
The first reason is
because we keep hearing,

00:09:12.550 --> 00:09:16.360 align:middle line:10%
as a society, that bad
things are to come,

00:09:16.360 --> 00:09:18.970 align:middle line:10%
because we are running out
of those resources that

00:09:18.970 --> 00:09:20.950 align:middle line:10%
have made our life possible--

00:09:20.950 --> 00:09:21.820 align:middle line:10%
oil.

00:09:21.820 --> 00:09:23.950 align:middle line:84%
Coal is of course
still abundant,

00:09:23.950 --> 00:09:26.520 align:middle line:84%
but it's not going to
be with us forever.

00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:28.580 align:middle line:84%
Resources are becoming
more and more expensive.

00:09:28.580 --> 00:09:31.300 align:middle line:10%
And so we hear that our
life is going to change.

00:09:31.300 --> 00:09:32.920 align:middle line:10%
Things are never
going to be the same.

00:09:32.920 --> 00:09:34.370 align:middle line:10%
I can't tell the future.

00:09:34.370 --> 00:09:35.810 align:middle line:90%
I can tell the present, though.

00:09:35.810 --> 00:09:37.780 align:middle line:10%
And I'm interested
in documenting

00:09:37.780 --> 00:09:41.080 align:middle line:10%
the lives of those people that
are living in the future today

00:09:41.080 --> 00:09:43.570 align:middle line:10%
and are relying on
renewable resources today.

00:09:43.570 --> 00:09:46.040 align:middle line:84%
And I'm interested in seeing
what their life is all about.

00:09:46.040 --> 00:09:51.290 align:middle line:90%


00:09:51.290 --> 00:09:53.933 align:middle line:84%
>> So what we do by traveling
the country and going to every

00:09:53.933 --> 00:09:56.350 align:middle line:84%
single province and territory,
we actually learn different

00:09:56.350 --> 00:10:00.115 align:middle line:84%
environments where people
adapt in different ways.

00:10:00.115 --> 00:10:01.330 align:middle line:90%
>> They let you do that?

00:10:01.330 --> 00:10:04.600 align:middle line:84%
>> Actually, I would say that
what has made our work possible

00:10:04.600 --> 00:10:07.420 align:middle line:84%
is the fact that pretty much
everyone who's off-grid wants

00:10:07.420 --> 00:10:09.520 align:middle line:90%
to teach others.

00:10:09.520 --> 00:10:11.980 align:middle line:84%
You and I probably don't
know half of the skills

00:10:11.980 --> 00:10:13.960 align:middle line:90%
that our grandparents had--

00:10:13.960 --> 00:10:18.180 align:middle line:84%
skills on how to
build a fire properly

00:10:18.180 --> 00:10:20.800 align:middle line:84%
or how to can your
vegetables that you've

00:10:20.800 --> 00:10:22.450 align:middle line:90%
grown in your garden.

00:10:22.450 --> 00:10:26.140 align:middle line:84%
And the idea is that if
we continue, as a society,

00:10:26.140 --> 00:10:29.650 align:middle line:84%
to forget these skills, we'll
be less and less self-sufficient

00:10:29.650 --> 00:10:32.110 align:middle line:84%
and more and more reliant
on distant providers that

00:10:32.110 --> 00:10:34.600 align:middle line:90%
burn non-renewable resources.

00:10:34.600 --> 00:10:51.980 align:middle line:90%


00:10:51.980 --> 00:10:55.580 align:middle line:84%
>> Generally, we like to begin
with a million dollar question.

00:10:55.580 --> 00:10:58.820 align:middle line:84%
We live in a country that
is, by historical and global

00:10:58.820 --> 00:11:03.050 align:middle line:84%
standards, a pretty
comfortable place.

00:11:03.050 --> 00:11:07.070 align:middle line:84%
We've got access to all kinds
of comforts and conveniences--

00:11:07.070 --> 00:11:08.840 align:middle line:84%
all technologies
that have supposedly

00:11:08.840 --> 00:11:12.870 align:middle line:90%
made our lives easier, better.

00:11:12.870 --> 00:11:14.730 align:middle line:84%
And here we have,
instead, a group

00:11:14.730 --> 00:11:17.640 align:middle line:84%
of people who go off-the-grid
and disconnect themselves

00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:20.080 align:middle line:90%
from this kind of world.

00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:21.488 align:middle line:10%
Why?

00:11:21.488 --> 00:11:22.288 align:middle line:10%
>> Good question.

00:11:22.288 --> 00:11:27.170 align:middle line:10%
>> [CHUCKLE] Told you, it
can get you going for hours.

00:11:27.170 --> 00:11:29.120 align:middle line:10%
>> Yeah.

00:11:29.120 --> 00:11:30.670 align:middle line:90%
Why, indeed.

00:11:30.670 --> 00:11:34.000 align:middle line:84%
There's a certain
amount of, let's see

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:36.680 align:middle line:90%
how little I can get by with.

00:11:36.680 --> 00:11:42.100 align:middle line:84%
Let's see how basic
I can make my life

00:11:42.100 --> 00:11:44.860 align:middle line:84%
or how simple I can
make my life and still

00:11:44.860 --> 00:11:47.990 align:middle line:90%
be happy and comfortable.

00:11:47.990 --> 00:11:52.840 align:middle line:84%
It's equal parts
necessity and philosophy.

00:11:52.840 --> 00:11:58.960 align:middle line:84%
When I decided that I wanted
to live at this location,

00:11:58.960 --> 00:12:02.820 align:middle line:84%
there was no option
of having electricity.

00:12:02.820 --> 00:12:04.700 align:middle line:84%
I mean, this location
was off-the-grid.

00:12:04.700 --> 00:12:06.970 align:middle line:90%
The grid was miles away.

00:12:06.970 --> 00:12:09.910 align:middle line:90%
There was no chance.

00:12:09.910 --> 00:12:12.670 align:middle line:84%
But I've stayed here so long
that the grid has actually

00:12:12.670 --> 00:12:15.280 align:middle line:84%
crept closer and
closer and closer.

00:12:15.280 --> 00:12:20.800 align:middle line:84%
We need more power because our
little farm has been growing.

00:12:20.800 --> 00:12:24.070 align:middle line:84%
And we had actually
made the decision

00:12:24.070 --> 00:12:28.180 align:middle line:84%
that we were going
to bite the bullet

00:12:28.180 --> 00:12:31.330 align:middle line:84%
and have the power come
the rest of the way.

00:12:31.330 --> 00:12:35.590 align:middle line:84%
And then we got into all
kinds of negotiations

00:12:35.590 --> 00:12:40.520 align:middle line:84%
and difficult things about
easements and whatnot, whatnot.

00:12:40.520 --> 00:12:42.970 align:middle line:90%
And it didn't pan out.

00:12:42.970 --> 00:12:47.320 align:middle line:10%
When that choice seemed to be
slipping through our fingers,

00:12:47.320 --> 00:12:53.830 align:middle line:10%
then we actually tripled
our solar capacity.

00:12:53.830 --> 00:12:59.290 align:middle line:90%


00:12:59.290 --> 00:13:02.240 align:middle line:84%
>> Brian, I wonder if someone
from Yukon Power came in today

00:13:02.240 --> 00:13:06.240 align:middle line:84%
and said, well, we're putting
a grid closer to your place

00:13:06.240 --> 00:13:07.620 align:middle line:90%
and no extra expense to you.

00:13:07.620 --> 00:13:08.810 align:middle line:90%
We can connect you.

00:13:08.810 --> 00:13:10.530 align:middle line:90%
Would you like to be connected?

00:13:10.530 --> 00:13:12.060 align:middle line:90%
What would you say to them?

00:13:12.060 --> 00:13:14.330 align:middle line:84%
>> I think we would do
it to get the power in.

00:13:14.330 --> 00:13:17.630 align:middle line:84%
We've been off-grid
for 30 years.

00:13:17.630 --> 00:13:19.450 align:middle line:90%
It's probably time.

00:13:19.450 --> 00:13:21.050 align:middle line:90%
I mean, this is our home.

00:13:21.050 --> 00:13:25.320 align:middle line:84%
We will probably
always live here.

00:13:25.320 --> 00:13:27.110 align:middle line:84%
How long we'll continue
to farm I guess

00:13:27.110 --> 00:13:30.380 align:middle line:84%
will depend on our level
of energy and stuff.

00:13:30.380 --> 00:13:35.450 align:middle line:84%
But I think we will live here
until we just absolutely cannot

00:13:35.450 --> 00:13:36.753 align:middle line:90%
live here anymore.

00:13:36.753 --> 00:13:49.080 align:middle line:90%


00:13:49.080 --> 00:13:52.460 align:middle line:84%
>> There's something that I
love, and I've always loved,

00:13:52.460 --> 00:13:58.910 align:middle line:84%
about the bush, the wilderness,
even as a child in California,

00:13:58.910 --> 00:14:00.920 align:middle line:84%
backpacking into
the high Sierras.

00:14:00.920 --> 00:14:03.400 align:middle line:84%
The decision to live
off-grid was not

00:14:03.400 --> 00:14:05.150 align:middle line:84%
saying we are determined
to live off-grid.

00:14:05.150 --> 00:14:08.510 align:middle line:84%
It was more, we're determined
to live in the bush.

00:14:08.510 --> 00:14:10.250 align:middle line:84%
And the only way to
do that was off-grid.

00:14:10.250 --> 00:14:15.060 align:middle line:84%
Because I meet people who are
similarly off-grid or whatever.

00:14:15.060 --> 00:14:19.250 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes it comes from an
apocalyptic view of the world.

00:14:19.250 --> 00:14:21.950 align:middle line:10%
And we had a guest
here the other day

00:14:21.950 --> 00:14:25.340 align:middle line:10%
who is very committed
to storing up food.

00:14:25.340 --> 00:14:27.012 align:middle line:10%
And he sees what--

00:14:27.012 --> 00:14:28.220 align:middle line:10%
>> Almost like a survivalist.

00:14:28.220 --> 00:14:29.820 align:middle line:84%
>> Yes, a survivalist
kind of thing.

00:14:29.820 --> 00:14:32.420 align:middle line:84%
I mean, he looks at what's
happening with the economy

00:14:32.420 --> 00:14:33.920 align:middle line:90%
and all these things.

00:14:33.920 --> 00:14:37.260 align:middle line:84%
And for him, it's
the precipice of--

00:14:37.260 --> 00:14:39.620 align:middle line:84%
and so he was
wondering what we had

00:14:39.620 --> 00:14:42.380 align:middle line:84%
been doing to make sure
that [CHUCKLE] we were ready

00:14:42.380 --> 00:14:44.350 align:middle line:90%
for the coming apocalypse.

00:14:44.350 --> 00:14:46.382 align:middle line:84%
So I'm not off-grid
in principle,

00:14:46.382 --> 00:14:47.840 align:middle line:84%
is probably the
best way to put it.

00:14:47.840 --> 00:14:51.140 align:middle line:90%
I would have used their power.

00:14:51.140 --> 00:14:55.370 align:middle line:84%
It's just not feasible,
economically--

00:14:55.370 --> 00:14:57.320 align:middle line:84%
>> How much would
it have cost you?

00:14:57.320 --> 00:15:00.768 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, I never
totally checked it out.

00:15:00.768 --> 00:15:03.310 align:middle line:84%
But I'm guessing a quarter of
a million dollars or something.

00:15:03.310 --> 00:15:05.352 align:middle line:90%
>> What?

00:15:05.352 --> 00:15:06.310 align:middle line:90%
>> It's a common thing.

00:15:06.310 --> 00:15:08.227 align:middle line:84%
The people come and they
see the wind turbine.

00:15:08.227 --> 00:15:10.520 align:middle line:84%
They see the solar
collectors and stuff.

00:15:10.520 --> 00:15:11.960 align:middle line:90%
And then they say, wow.

00:15:11.960 --> 00:15:13.905 align:middle line:90%
You get your power for free.

00:15:13.905 --> 00:15:15.780 align:middle line:84%
And I always have to
laugh and say, well, no.

00:15:15.780 --> 00:15:20.690 align:middle line:84%
Actually, what I did was I paid
for 30 years of power upfront.

00:15:20.690 --> 00:15:22.610 align:middle line:90%
[CHUCKLE]

00:15:22.610 --> 00:15:26.180 align:middle line:84%
When there's excess power, the
batteries are fully charged.

00:15:26.180 --> 00:15:28.670 align:middle line:10%
So if the wind is blowing
and the sun is shining

00:15:28.670 --> 00:15:30.170 align:middle line:10%
and the batteries
are fully charged,

00:15:30.170 --> 00:15:31.850 align:middle line:10%
basically it's just dumping--

00:15:31.850 --> 00:15:35.620 align:middle line:10%
we have more power
than we can use.

00:15:35.620 --> 00:15:42.330 align:middle line:84%
So here is what I call the
upper array because there's

00:15:42.330 --> 00:15:44.670 align:middle line:90%
the lower array.

00:15:44.670 --> 00:15:51.900 align:middle line:90%
So each of these is 175 watts.

00:15:51.900 --> 00:15:54.875 align:middle line:90%
So 6 times 175--

00:15:54.875 --> 00:15:56.122 align:middle line:90%
>> There's 12 of them.

00:15:56.122 --> 00:15:57.330 align:middle line:90%
>> And there are 12 of them--

00:15:57.330 --> 00:15:59.500 align:middle line:90%
24 altogether.

00:15:59.500 --> 00:16:01.510 align:middle line:84%
>> Now how did you learn
to do all this stuff?

00:16:01.510 --> 00:16:05.890 align:middle line:90%


00:16:05.890 --> 00:16:07.170 align:middle line:90%
>> By trying.

00:16:07.170 --> 00:16:08.538 align:middle line:90%
And I made mistakes, but--

00:16:08.538 --> 00:16:09.580 align:middle line:90%
so you had to redo stuff.

00:16:09.580 --> 00:16:11.020 align:middle line:90%
So I wasn't speedy.

00:16:11.020 --> 00:16:13.600 align:middle line:84%
Reading, researching,
trial and error,

00:16:13.600 --> 00:16:15.140 align:middle line:90%
and asking questions you know.

00:16:15.140 --> 00:16:15.940 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:16:15.940 --> 00:16:17.520 align:middle line:84%
Seeking advice from
people who know

00:16:17.520 --> 00:16:19.630 align:middle line:84%
and who were happy to
share their knowledge.

00:16:19.630 --> 00:16:20.838 align:middle line:90%
I mean, think about anything.

00:16:20.838 --> 00:16:24.415 align:middle line:84%
If you thought about any
kind of project and--

00:16:24.415 --> 00:16:26.590 align:middle line:84%
as a whole and said,
how can I do that?

00:16:26.590 --> 00:16:27.975 align:middle line:90%
It's overwhelming.

00:16:27.975 --> 00:16:30.100 align:middle line:84%
But it's the old adage,
how do you eat an elephant?

00:16:30.100 --> 00:16:31.250 align:middle line:90%
One bite at a time.

00:16:31.250 --> 00:16:34.930 align:middle line:84%
And so I didn't have to
figure out everything

00:16:34.930 --> 00:16:36.700 align:middle line:90%
before I figured out this part.

00:16:36.700 --> 00:16:40.142 align:middle line:84%
And as this part evolved, then I
needed to figure out this part.

00:16:40.142 --> 00:16:41.350 align:middle line:90%
Then I figured out that part.

00:16:41.350 --> 00:16:45.010 align:middle line:84%
And as you move along,
it evolves and it works.

00:16:45.010 --> 00:16:46.510 align:middle line:84%
Then you find your
way step by step.

00:16:46.510 --> 00:16:49.830 align:middle line:84%
And it's only looking back that
you realize, oh my goodness.

00:16:49.830 --> 00:16:51.010 align:middle line:90%
Wow.

00:16:51.010 --> 00:16:52.210 align:middle line:90%
How did I pull that off?

00:16:52.210 --> 00:16:59.330 align:middle line:90%


00:16:59.330 --> 00:17:01.710 align:middle line:90%
>> I live on a small island.

00:17:01.710 --> 00:17:04.130 align:middle line:84%
I am self-reliant for
my own water supply.

00:17:04.130 --> 00:17:08.060 align:middle line:84%
And when I moved there,
I realized how much

00:17:08.060 --> 00:17:09.859 align:middle line:84%
your attitude
changes when you are

00:17:09.859 --> 00:17:11.240 align:middle line:90%
self-sufficient for something.

00:17:11.240 --> 00:17:13.200 align:middle line:84%
And you're much more
careful with it.

00:17:13.200 --> 00:17:16.760 align:middle line:84%
And I wanted to see if other
people also were as careful.

00:17:16.760 --> 00:17:18.950 align:middle line:84%
>> You have somebody
taping this right now,

00:17:18.950 --> 00:17:21.470 align:middle line:84%
so you're kind of documenting
everything as you go along.

00:17:21.470 --> 00:17:22.400 align:middle line:90%
>> We work nonstop.

00:17:22.400 --> 00:17:23.200 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:17:23.200 --> 00:17:25.700 align:middle line:84%
And so this is really
becoming-- this, I guess,

00:17:25.700 --> 00:17:27.269 align:middle line:90%
is part of ethnography to--

00:17:27.269 --> 00:17:28.069 align:middle line:90%
>> Oh, absolutely.

00:17:28.069 --> 00:17:30.380 align:middle line:84%
>> --document in
whatever way you can.

00:17:30.380 --> 00:17:33.660 align:middle line:84%
If people listening want to
get in touch, can they do that?

00:17:33.660 --> 00:17:34.460 align:middle line:90%
>> Oh, absolutely.

00:17:34.460 --> 00:17:35.260 align:middle line:90%
I would love to.

00:17:35.260 --> 00:17:37.420 align:middle line:84%
If they're off-the-grid,
we'll make our way there.

00:17:37.420 --> 00:18:01.060 align:middle line:90%


00:18:01.060 --> 00:18:05.980 align:middle line:84%
>> If you look back on any
life, it's a bunch of stepping

00:18:05.980 --> 00:18:06.810 align:middle line:90%
stones.

00:18:06.810 --> 00:18:09.460 align:middle line:84%
And you just never know where
they're going to take you.

00:18:09.460 --> 00:18:15.490 align:middle line:84%
So my training was
industrial electronics.

00:18:15.490 --> 00:18:21.010 align:middle line:84%
And Joanna was a
registered dietitian.

00:18:21.010 --> 00:18:27.640 align:middle line:84%
And I was working at a
company, electronics company.

00:18:27.640 --> 00:18:30.700 align:middle line:84%
And I just felt there
had to be more to life.

00:18:30.700 --> 00:18:33.850 align:middle line:10%
Joanna came up with the
floor plan for the house

00:18:33.850 --> 00:18:35.650 align:middle line:10%
that she wanted to have.

00:18:35.650 --> 00:18:43.030 align:middle line:84%
So I took the floor
plans and I researched

00:18:43.030 --> 00:18:45.130 align:middle line:84%
construction
techniques that would

00:18:45.130 --> 00:18:47.410 align:middle line:90%
deal with a harsher climate.

00:18:47.410 --> 00:18:51.730 align:middle line:84%
And I was not impressed
with what I researched.

00:18:51.730 --> 00:18:55.160 align:middle line:84%
So I came up with
a unique design.

00:18:55.160 --> 00:18:57.760 align:middle line:84%
I've never seen
anybody else do it.

00:18:57.760 --> 00:19:01.400 align:middle line:10%
>> Well, everything has
worked better than I expected.

00:19:01.400 --> 00:19:05.290 align:middle line:10%
I didn't know a lot of the
things I've learned because I--

00:19:05.290 --> 00:19:08.140 align:middle line:10%
every challenge we came
up against, what did I do?

00:19:08.140 --> 00:19:09.450 align:middle line:90%
Some research.

00:19:09.450 --> 00:19:11.840 align:middle line:84%
I found out how to
do it and I did it.

00:19:11.840 --> 00:19:13.760 align:middle line:90%
It's as simple as that.

00:19:13.760 --> 00:19:15.760 align:middle line:84%
And people say, well, how
did you get this done?

00:19:15.760 --> 00:19:17.580 align:middle line:90%
Or you can't do that.

00:19:17.580 --> 00:19:19.560 align:middle line:90%
Well, that's nonsense.

00:19:19.560 --> 00:19:21.730 align:middle line:90%
Of course I can do it.

00:19:21.730 --> 00:19:23.860 align:middle line:10%
We haven't run up
against anything

00:19:23.860 --> 00:19:27.010 align:middle line:10%
that we haven't been able
to do or handle ourselves.

00:19:27.010 --> 00:19:29.030 align:middle line:90%
We're retired school teachers.

00:19:29.030 --> 00:19:30.790 align:middle line:90%
And we spent--

00:19:30.790 --> 00:19:32.050 align:middle line:90%
>> 35 years in town.

00:19:32.050 --> 00:19:33.860 align:middle line:90%
>> 35 years in the town.

00:19:33.860 --> 00:19:37.280 align:middle line:84%
And what we wanted to
do when we retired--

00:19:37.280 --> 00:19:39.520 align:middle line:84%
the first thing we did
was sell the house in town

00:19:39.520 --> 00:19:41.010 align:middle line:90%
and move out here to the bush.

00:19:41.010 --> 00:19:43.520 align:middle line:84%
>> Basically we've got
everything we could possibly

00:19:43.520 --> 00:19:44.320 align:middle line:90%
want.

00:19:44.320 --> 00:19:46.123 align:middle line:90%
>> You've got all the comfort--

00:19:46.123 --> 00:19:47.290 align:middle line:90%
>> All the comforts of home.

00:19:47.290 --> 00:19:49.010 align:middle line:84%
>> All the necessary
conveniences?

00:19:49.010 --> 00:19:49.810 align:middle line:90%
>> Mm-hmm.

00:19:49.810 --> 00:19:51.730 align:middle line:90%
>> We watch all the TV.

00:19:51.730 --> 00:19:53.710 align:middle line:90%
We listen to the stereo.

00:19:53.710 --> 00:19:55.700 align:middle line:84%
We have all the lights
that we want on.

00:19:55.700 --> 00:19:56.500 align:middle line:90%
We--

00:19:56.500 --> 00:19:57.670 align:middle line:90%
>> Have a computer.

00:19:57.670 --> 00:19:59.020 align:middle line:90%
>> We run the coffeemaker.

00:19:59.020 --> 00:20:03.340 align:middle line:84%
We run-- [CHUCKLE] We do
all those kinds of things.

00:20:03.340 --> 00:20:06.680 align:middle line:84%
>> It's a rare
thing, fortunately,

00:20:06.680 --> 00:20:10.030 align:middle line:84%
that I haven't been able to fix
something or jury-rig something

00:20:10.030 --> 00:20:11.590 align:middle line:90%
to get it to go.

00:20:11.590 --> 00:20:14.720 align:middle line:84%
>> You must have had some
contract to do some part--

00:20:14.720 --> 00:20:15.520 align:middle line:90%
>> Nothing.

00:20:15.520 --> 00:20:16.000 align:middle line:90%
>> Nothing.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:16.990 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely nothing.

00:20:16.990 --> 00:20:17.920 align:middle line:90%
>> We've done it all ourselves.

00:20:17.920 --> 00:20:19.212 align:middle line:90%
>> I did absolutely everything.

00:20:19.212 --> 00:20:23.740 align:middle line:10%
>> Part of living out here
is having an inventory

00:20:23.740 --> 00:20:29.400 align:middle line:10%
and anticipating what things
and spare parts are you going

00:20:29.400 --> 00:20:30.200 align:middle line:10%
to need.

00:20:30.200 --> 00:20:34.060 align:middle line:84%
>> We have degrees coming out
of our ears from this place.

00:20:34.060 --> 00:20:34.860 align:middle line:90%
>> So many books.

00:20:34.860 --> 00:20:36.960 align:middle line:84%
>> So we have tons
and tons of books.

00:20:36.960 --> 00:20:40.070 align:middle line:84%
>> With anything, machine
or engine-wise, I mean,

00:20:40.070 --> 00:20:43.120 align:middle line:84%
there are certain things that
you can take a wild stab at.

00:20:43.120 --> 00:20:46.013 align:middle line:90%


00:20:46.013 --> 00:20:46.930 align:middle line:90%
>> I built this thing.

00:20:46.930 --> 00:20:49.000 align:middle line:84%
And then she said, oh,
well, that's not enough.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:51.580 align:middle line:84%
>> And generally, if something's
going to break down, I mean,

00:20:51.580 --> 00:20:53.140 align:middle line:84%
it's going to be
something simple.

00:20:53.140 --> 00:20:55.870 align:middle line:84%
>> Just this fall, I built this
air compressor out of a lawn

00:20:55.870 --> 00:20:57.220 align:middle line:90%
mower motor.

00:20:57.220 --> 00:21:00.700 align:middle line:84%
>> Very rarely have we had
to deal with something that

00:21:00.700 --> 00:21:02.110 align:middle line:90%
couldn't be fixed out here.

00:21:02.110 --> 00:21:04.722 align:middle line:84%
The generator was
definitely one of them.

00:21:04.722 --> 00:21:05.680 align:middle line:90%
I guess that's really--

00:21:05.680 --> 00:21:07.180 align:middle line:90%
>> Well, the first wind turbine.

00:21:07.180 --> 00:21:08.900 align:middle line:90%
That was the second one.

00:21:08.900 --> 00:21:10.750 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, but that's
not our problem.

00:21:10.750 --> 00:21:13.690 align:middle line:90%
I mean, that's faulty.

00:21:13.690 --> 00:21:18.680 align:middle line:84%
Or we could debate
the design of that.

00:21:18.680 --> 00:21:21.270 align:middle line:90%
>> Oh, there's a million things.

00:21:21.270 --> 00:21:23.052 align:middle line:84%
I also want to build
an electric car.

00:21:23.052 --> 00:21:24.500 align:middle line:90%
[CHUCKLE]

00:21:24.500 --> 00:21:33.920 align:middle line:84%
>> It's definitely a feeling
that most of the population is

00:21:33.920 --> 00:21:37.310 align:middle line:90%
really dependent on others.

00:21:37.310 --> 00:21:42.590 align:middle line:84%
And being out here, we're
dependent on ourselves.

00:21:42.590 --> 00:21:49.760 align:middle line:90%


00:21:49.760 --> 00:21:52.580 align:middle line:84%
>> The oven is a little bit
tricky sometimes to get used

00:21:52.580 --> 00:21:53.420 align:middle line:90%
to.

00:21:53.420 --> 00:21:58.850 align:middle line:84%
But once you get the
hang of it, I don't know,

00:21:58.850 --> 00:22:01.790 align:middle line:84%
it just becomes
like second nature.

00:22:01.790 --> 00:22:04.190 align:middle line:84%
If I was to have this
on all day long, even

00:22:04.190 --> 00:22:06.620 align:middle line:84%
in the wintertime
on a sunny day,

00:22:06.620 --> 00:22:08.420 align:middle line:84%
it would get
stiflingly hot in here.

00:22:08.420 --> 00:22:12.000 align:middle line:90%


00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:15.050 align:middle line:84%
>> What's really important
in this country is that,

00:22:15.050 --> 00:22:18.080 align:middle line:84%
first of all, we have massive
amounts of insulation.

00:22:18.080 --> 00:22:20.220 align:middle line:90%
That's the most important thing.

00:22:20.220 --> 00:22:25.640 align:middle line:84%
The second thing is that we
have tons of material that

00:22:25.640 --> 00:22:27.380 align:middle line:90%
can be used as thermal mass.

00:22:27.380 --> 00:22:31.070 align:middle line:84%
So once you warm it up, it
retains the heat and radiates

00:22:31.070 --> 00:22:32.930 align:middle line:90%
heat for days and days and days.

00:22:32.930 --> 00:22:35.030 align:middle line:84%
Here, for example,
I have 5,000 gallons

00:22:35.030 --> 00:22:38.090 align:middle line:84%
of water in the crawlspace
under the floor,

00:22:38.090 --> 00:22:40.580 align:middle line:90%
under where you're sitting--

00:22:40.580 --> 00:22:42.290 align:middle line:84%
always different jugs,
different sizes--

00:22:42.290 --> 00:22:45.385 align:middle line:84%
2 gallon jugs, 5 gallon
jugs, 13 gallon jugs--

00:22:45.385 --> 00:22:47.630 align:middle line:84%
>> Soap and wax jugs,
that sort of thing.

00:22:47.630 --> 00:22:51.690 align:middle line:84%
>> --that originally had soap
and wax and laundry detergent.

00:22:51.690 --> 00:22:52.490 align:middle line:90%
And some of these--

00:22:52.490 --> 00:22:54.698 align:middle line:84%
I've been collecting these
from the hotels in Dawson.

00:22:54.698 --> 00:22:57.190 align:middle line:90%


00:22:57.190 --> 00:22:58.190 align:middle line:90%
They don't recycle them.

00:22:58.190 --> 00:23:00.085 align:middle line:90%
They just throw them away.

00:23:00.085 --> 00:23:02.210 align:middle line:84%
>> These are questions that
I haven't asked before,

00:23:02.210 --> 00:23:03.590 align:middle line:90%
because you guys are so remote.

00:23:03.590 --> 00:23:09.320 align:middle line:84%
How often do you leave the
house on a yearly basis

00:23:09.320 --> 00:23:10.140 align:middle line:90%
or monthly basis?

00:23:10.140 --> 00:23:10.940 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:23:10.940 --> 00:23:12.650 align:middle line:90%
>> Generally, twice a year.

00:23:12.650 --> 00:23:17.150 align:middle line:84%
Usually in spring, like March,
before the ice goes out.

00:23:17.150 --> 00:23:19.520 align:middle line:84%
And then in the fall,
end of September,

00:23:19.520 --> 00:23:22.880 align:middle line:84%
beginning of October, before
the ice starts forming.

00:23:22.880 --> 00:23:24.560 align:middle line:84%
>> Our daughter
lives in Edmonton,

00:23:24.560 --> 00:23:26.210 align:middle line:84%
and we go and visit
her quite often.

00:23:26.210 --> 00:23:27.890 align:middle line:84%
And our son lives
in Dawson Creek,

00:23:27.890 --> 00:23:30.770 align:middle line:90%
which is only 35 miles away.

00:23:30.770 --> 00:23:33.560 align:middle line:84%
But we have a lot of friends
that come from other cities

00:23:33.560 --> 00:23:39.050 align:middle line:84%
and camp out here with us,
in the summer especially.

00:23:39.050 --> 00:23:42.890 align:middle line:84%
>> We're comfortable
with our own company.

00:23:42.890 --> 00:23:47.700 align:middle line:84%
We're not antisocial, but we're
just happy to be out here.

00:23:47.700 --> 00:23:49.820 align:middle line:90%
We have no set schedule.

00:23:49.820 --> 00:23:54.240 align:middle line:10%
We see the rest of the world
as working and spinning

00:23:54.240 --> 00:24:01.250 align:middle line:10%
their wheels like a hamster in
a cage trying to just make money

00:24:01.250 --> 00:24:03.362 align:middle line:10%
to live and survive.

00:24:03.362 --> 00:24:04.820 align:middle line:84%
>> Aren't you afraid
of loneliness?

00:24:04.820 --> 00:24:06.180 align:middle line:90%
Aren't you afraid of just--

00:24:06.180 --> 00:24:06.980 align:middle line:90%
>> No.

00:24:06.980 --> 00:24:09.720 align:middle line:10%
>> Isn't it intimidating to
be all by yourself out here?

00:24:09.720 --> 00:24:10.820 align:middle line:10%
>> Uh-uh.

00:24:10.820 --> 00:24:14.270 align:middle line:10%
>> I think initially I was
a little bit nervous about,

00:24:14.270 --> 00:24:18.480 align:middle line:10%
how am I going to react to that?

00:24:18.480 --> 00:24:23.900 align:middle line:10%
But I'm basically an introvert
to begin with, so I'm not--

00:24:23.900 --> 00:24:26.120 align:middle line:10%
like Ron said, we're
not antisocial.

00:24:26.120 --> 00:24:28.760 align:middle line:10%
I mean, we had friends
when we were in Maine.

00:24:28.760 --> 00:24:31.230 align:middle line:84%
I had friends that
I worked with.

00:24:31.230 --> 00:24:33.980 align:middle line:84%
But we're not social
butterflies either.

00:24:33.980 --> 00:24:59.620 align:middle line:90%


00:24:59.620 --> 00:25:04.140 align:middle line:84%
>> When the road is open,
between freeze up and break up,

00:25:04.140 --> 00:25:06.160 align:middle line:90%
I make a trip every three weeks.

00:25:06.160 --> 00:25:08.970 align:middle line:84%
And when I'm done loading my
truck, everything on that truck

00:25:08.970 --> 00:25:11.700 align:middle line:90%
is paid for.

00:25:11.700 --> 00:25:15.240 align:middle line:84%
And then I bring it
here and sell it.

00:25:15.240 --> 00:25:18.330 align:middle line:10%
If I could go down into
Washington State into Seattle

00:25:18.330 --> 00:25:20.550 align:middle line:10%
or someplace like
that without having

00:25:20.550 --> 00:25:22.890 align:middle line:10%
to go through the hassle
of the border or whatever,

00:25:22.890 --> 00:25:27.383 align:middle line:10%
I would do that because it's
going to be that much fresher.

00:25:27.383 --> 00:25:28.800 align:middle line:84%
You never know
what the prices are

00:25:28.800 --> 00:25:31.410 align:middle line:84%
going to be from one trip to
the next anyway, you know?

00:25:31.410 --> 00:25:38.280 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I've paid a price
for, say, broccoli one trip.

00:25:38.280 --> 00:25:41.750 align:middle line:84%
And the very next trip three
weeks later, it'll be double.

00:25:41.750 --> 00:25:43.390 align:middle line:90%
It's all supply and demand.

00:25:43.390 --> 00:25:47.800 align:middle line:90%


00:25:47.800 --> 00:25:50.100 align:middle line:84%
>> So what you have now is
a town that only grew to 3

00:25:50.100 --> 00:25:52.630 align:middle line:84%
and 1/2 thousand-- although
it was projected to one day go

00:25:52.630 --> 00:25:53.110 align:middle line:90%
to 10.

00:25:53.110 --> 00:25:54.193 align:middle line:90%
And everything's laid out.

00:25:54.193 --> 00:25:55.510 align:middle line:90%
We get the needs over there.

00:25:55.510 --> 00:25:57.600 align:middle line:10%
We do have our
year-round water supply.

00:25:57.600 --> 00:25:59.770 align:middle line:10%
We, of course, have, the road.

00:25:59.770 --> 00:26:02.170 align:middle line:10%
Shipping still comes
in on the river.

00:26:02.170 --> 00:26:04.993 align:middle line:90%
We still have the highway.

00:26:04.993 --> 00:26:07.160 align:middle line:84%
Basically, we've got a fully
functional town sitting

00:26:07.160 --> 00:26:09.370 align:middle line:84%
in the middle of nowhere
in the Arctic, which

00:26:09.370 --> 00:26:13.400 align:middle line:90%
is really quite fascinating.

00:26:13.400 --> 00:26:16.045 align:middle line:10%
>> A lot of times, when
researchers or people from

00:26:16.045 --> 00:26:18.420 align:middle line:10%
the south-- whether they're
journalists-- come to Inuvik,

00:26:18.420 --> 00:26:21.623 align:middle line:10%
they come up and try and
sometimes sensationalize-- oh,

00:26:21.623 --> 00:26:22.790 align:middle line:10%
we're in the isolated north.

00:26:22.790 --> 00:26:26.090 align:middle line:10%
But when you're living here--
and I've been here 18 years--

00:26:26.090 --> 00:26:28.100 align:middle line:10%
it's no different than
any small town in Canada.

00:26:28.100 --> 00:26:30.590 align:middle line:84%
You'd need a town of
probably about 60,000 people

00:26:30.590 --> 00:26:32.480 align:middle line:84%
to get the amenities
that we have here.

00:26:32.480 --> 00:26:34.830 align:middle line:84%
And I know we're off-the-grid,
and you say, well--

00:26:34.830 --> 00:26:37.200 align:middle line:84%
and you look at the
map and where we are.

00:26:37.200 --> 00:26:39.020 align:middle line:84%
But Inuvik is a
small town in Canada.

00:26:39.020 --> 00:26:41.020 align:middle line:84%
And it could be a small
town anywhere in Canada.

00:26:41.020 --> 00:26:44.430 align:middle line:90%


00:26:44.430 --> 00:26:48.390 align:middle line:84%
>> Yes, starting
mid-to-late October.

00:26:48.390 --> 00:26:51.980 align:middle line:10%
That's when it starts because
things start to freeze

00:26:51.980 --> 00:26:54.080 align:middle line:10%
in the two river crossings.

00:26:54.080 --> 00:26:57.140 align:middle line:10%
And it's impossible
to take a boat across.

00:26:57.140 --> 00:26:59.270 align:middle line:10%
So they have to close
the ferry crossings

00:26:59.270 --> 00:27:01.760 align:middle line:10%
and just wait until
it's frozen enough

00:27:01.760 --> 00:27:05.273 align:middle line:10%
that you can then drive across.

00:27:05.273 --> 00:27:07.190 align:middle line:84%
When they're doing that,
during the freeze up,

00:27:07.190 --> 00:27:10.670 align:middle line:84%
everything perishable
has to be flown in.

00:27:10.670 --> 00:27:15.350 align:middle line:10%
So the cost of dairy products
goes through the roof.

00:27:15.350 --> 00:27:17.930 align:middle line:10%
The flip side of it,
the actual break up--

00:27:17.930 --> 00:27:21.860 align:middle line:10%
when that happens in May, that's
when people are celebrating

00:27:21.860 --> 00:27:25.040 align:middle line:10%
or placing bets as to what
day the river will break up.

00:27:25.040 --> 00:27:27.230 align:middle line:90%
That ice road is--

00:27:27.230 --> 00:27:30.140 align:middle line:84%
it's kind of an artery for
transportation around here

00:27:30.140 --> 00:27:33.440 align:middle line:84%
because a lot of local
folks have camps.

00:27:33.440 --> 00:27:35.820 align:middle line:10%
And they can take the ice road--

00:27:35.820 --> 00:27:38.360 align:middle line:10%
can take their Ski-Doo
out there and just go up

00:27:38.360 --> 00:27:41.300 align:middle line:10%
to their camp that's
off the river.

00:27:41.300 --> 00:27:43.100 align:middle line:90%
>> I have three cabins, really.

00:27:43.100 --> 00:27:46.180 align:middle line:84%
I've got the winter
one for trapping.

00:27:46.180 --> 00:27:48.680 align:middle line:84%
I have the summer
one for whales.

00:27:48.680 --> 00:27:53.750 align:middle line:10%
And I have the fall one
for hunting the caribou.

00:27:53.750 --> 00:28:02.060 align:middle line:10%
And our whale, our beluga whale,
we get that in the summertime.

00:28:02.060 --> 00:28:06.750 align:middle line:84%
It is a way of subsidizing
ourselves because of--

00:28:06.750 --> 00:28:07.550 align:middle line:90%
we can do it.

00:28:07.550 --> 00:28:08.810 align:middle line:90%
It's our right.

00:28:08.810 --> 00:28:11.780 align:middle line:84%
Before the weather
gets too warm here,

00:28:11.780 --> 00:28:13.760 align:middle line:84%
we try to bring all the
heavy stuff on the road

00:28:13.760 --> 00:28:17.480 align:middle line:90%
or by Ski-Doos to the camp.

00:28:17.480 --> 00:28:21.900 align:middle line:84%
Up here, we know how
to travel on that ice.

00:28:21.900 --> 00:28:28.140 align:middle line:84%
For me, it is taught to me from
my grandfather and my father.

00:28:28.140 --> 00:28:32.430 align:middle line:10%
I'm pretty confident in what
I do when I travel out there.

00:28:32.430 --> 00:28:34.550 align:middle line:10%
If I'm not confident,
then I won't go.

00:28:34.550 --> 00:28:38.060 align:middle line:10%
If I'm confident, I'll go.

00:28:38.060 --> 00:28:39.060 align:middle line:10%
It's just how I travel.

00:28:39.060 --> 00:28:41.964 align:middle line:90%


00:28:41.964 --> 00:28:45.352 align:middle line:90%
[SNOWMOBILE SOUND]

00:28:45.352 --> 00:28:50.676 align:middle line:90%


00:28:50.676 --> 00:28:54.570 align:middle line:84%
>> [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]
This is where we are now.

00:28:54.570 --> 00:29:01.430 align:middle line:90%


00:29:01.430 --> 00:29:12.510 align:middle line:10%
Yesterday we went up this
way and part of this river.

00:29:12.510 --> 00:29:20.100 align:middle line:84%
And then we went this
valley, through that lake.

00:29:20.100 --> 00:29:24.750 align:middle line:90%


00:29:24.750 --> 00:29:26.495 align:middle line:90%
>> So that's where we've been.

00:29:26.495 --> 00:29:28.290 align:middle line:90%
>> Those are nice maps.

00:29:28.290 --> 00:29:31.909 align:middle line:90%
>> Way far away from anywhere.

00:29:31.909 --> 00:29:35.402 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:29:35.402 --> 00:30:26.300 align:middle line:90%


00:30:26.300 --> 00:30:28.795 align:middle line:90%
>> Go that way.

00:30:28.795 --> 00:30:32.288 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:30:32.288 --> 00:32:05.102 align:middle line:90%


00:32:05.102 --> 00:32:08.595 align:middle line:90%
[WIND BLOWING]

00:32:08.595 --> 00:32:18.076 align:middle line:90%


00:32:18.076 --> 00:32:21.569 align:middle line:90%
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

00:32:21.569 --> 00:33:05.100 align:middle line:90%


00:33:05.100 --> 00:33:08.700 align:middle line:84%
>> As far as I can remember,
I've always wanted to have

00:33:08.700 --> 00:33:12.360 align:middle line:90%
my own house because that's--

00:33:12.360 --> 00:33:18.750 align:middle line:84%
I was already drawing houses
that looked like this.

00:33:18.750 --> 00:33:21.960 align:middle line:10%
The only difference was
that I was using cement

00:33:21.960 --> 00:33:24.165 align:middle line:10%
to build the walls.

00:33:24.165 --> 00:33:28.760 align:middle line:84%
An earthship is an idea that
came to Michael Reynolds

00:33:28.760 --> 00:33:31.500 align:middle line:90%
about 35 years ago.

00:33:31.500 --> 00:33:33.750 align:middle line:84%
He wanted to build
a house that would

00:33:33.750 --> 00:33:37.770 align:middle line:84%
be easy to build for
everybody so everybody

00:33:37.770 --> 00:33:41.050 align:middle line:84%
could have a house instead
of having a mortgage.

00:33:41.050 --> 00:33:46.890 align:middle line:84%
So they made the earthship
as to be autonomous, create

00:33:46.890 --> 00:33:52.860 align:middle line:84%
its own power,
collect its own water,

00:33:52.860 --> 00:33:55.350 align:middle line:84%
reuse the water as
much as possible,

00:33:55.350 --> 00:34:01.020 align:middle line:84%
and also build it out of
material that is available.

00:34:01.020 --> 00:34:05.850 align:middle line:84%
And the principal
component that everybody

00:34:05.850 --> 00:34:09.840 align:middle line:84%
talks about when talking about
an earthship is the tires.

00:34:09.840 --> 00:34:13.380 align:middle line:84%
And you just basically
use the tires

00:34:13.380 --> 00:34:17.820 align:middle line:90%
as a form to pound dirt into it.

00:34:17.820 --> 00:34:22.590 align:middle line:84%
So it's really a
land-earth house

00:34:22.590 --> 00:34:25.230 align:middle line:84%
where the tires are used as
a form that stays in place.

00:34:25.230 --> 00:34:31.060 align:middle line:90%


00:34:31.060 --> 00:34:34.810 align:middle line:84%
So this is tires and--
covered with mud.

00:34:34.810 --> 00:34:39.690 align:middle line:84%
And then there is a
lime plaster finish.

00:34:39.690 --> 00:34:41.280 align:middle line:90%
They provide mass.

00:34:41.280 --> 00:34:46.710 align:middle line:84%
So they're like a battery
that stores heat or drains

00:34:46.710 --> 00:34:49.900 align:middle line:90%
heat when it's too warm.

00:34:49.900 --> 00:34:52.680 align:middle line:84%
>> So are these Michelin,
Goodyear, Pirelli?

00:34:52.680 --> 00:34:53.480 align:middle line:90%
Just kidding.

00:34:53.480 --> 00:34:59.370 align:middle line:84%
>> Doesn't matter the make,
only that it's for a season.

00:34:59.370 --> 00:35:02.540 align:middle line:84%
>> My design comes
from the earth, really.

00:35:02.540 --> 00:35:05.580 align:middle line:84%
I look at the
rocks and I go, OK,

00:35:05.580 --> 00:35:08.040 align:middle line:84%
this makes sense
for a cob building--

00:35:08.040 --> 00:35:11.700 align:middle line:84%
sense in the sense
of less work for me.

00:35:11.700 --> 00:35:13.860 align:middle line:10%
I looked at where
the rocks were.

00:35:13.860 --> 00:35:17.220 align:middle line:10%
And a lot of the foundation
of the main house

00:35:17.220 --> 00:35:22.188 align:middle line:10%
was not needed to be built
because it was already there.

00:35:22.188 --> 00:35:23.730 align:middle line:84%
>> This is called
a cob house, right?

00:35:23.730 --> 00:35:24.530 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:35:24.530 --> 00:35:26.310 align:middle line:90%
What you're feeling is plaster.

00:35:26.310 --> 00:35:29.400 align:middle line:84%
But inside, which you can
see on the outside easily,

00:35:29.400 --> 00:35:33.210 align:middle line:84%
is a mixture of sand, clay,
and straw mixed together

00:35:33.210 --> 00:35:34.440 align:middle line:90%
with water.

00:35:34.440 --> 00:35:37.770 align:middle line:90%
And it's a sculptural technique.

00:35:37.770 --> 00:35:41.540 align:middle line:84%
There's no posts here
holding up the roof at all.

00:35:41.540 --> 00:35:44.950 align:middle line:84%
The cob itself is strong
enough to do that.

00:35:44.950 --> 00:35:46.920 align:middle line:84%
It's a technique
that's been used

00:35:46.920 --> 00:35:50.100 align:middle line:84%
by humans for millions of
years, more or less-- earthquake

00:35:50.100 --> 00:35:51.090 align:middle line:90%
proof.

00:35:51.090 --> 00:35:53.970 align:middle line:90%
It's insect proof, rodent proof.

00:35:53.970 --> 00:35:55.140 align:middle line:90%
It's dirt cheap.

00:35:55.140 --> 00:36:00.810 align:middle line:84%
I probably paid $200 to $300
for the sand to be delivered.

00:36:00.810 --> 00:36:03.960 align:middle line:84%
And I don't know
what else I paid for.

00:36:03.960 --> 00:36:06.900 align:middle line:90%
I mean, I bought the doors used.

00:36:06.900 --> 00:36:09.690 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, this whole place,
which is very small--

00:36:09.690 --> 00:36:13.880 align:middle line:90%
but I might have spent $1,000.

00:36:13.880 --> 00:36:17.730 align:middle line:10%
>> Is there some kind of energy
efficient genius behind--

00:36:17.730 --> 00:36:18.670 align:middle line:10%
>> No, not really.

00:36:18.670 --> 00:36:19.470 align:middle line:10%
>> OK.

00:36:19.470 --> 00:36:20.580 align:middle line:10%
So style?

00:36:20.580 --> 00:36:21.400 align:middle line:10%
>> It was just--

00:36:21.400 --> 00:36:23.190 align:middle line:10%
it's very cheap.

00:36:23.190 --> 00:36:26.130 align:middle line:10%
Part of living off-the-grid
for me has always

00:36:26.130 --> 00:36:29.460 align:middle line:10%
been living with less money.

00:36:29.460 --> 00:36:30.480 align:middle line:10%
Wood is cheap.

00:36:30.480 --> 00:36:35.520 align:middle line:10%
And metal roofing and
foundations are expensive.

00:36:35.520 --> 00:36:38.610 align:middle line:10%
So I thought, I'll get
extra square footage

00:36:38.610 --> 00:36:42.030 align:middle line:10%
for cheap by building
lots of floors.

00:36:42.030 --> 00:36:45.120 align:middle line:84%
When I started this house, I
might have had a couple grand

00:36:45.120 --> 00:36:48.650 align:middle line:84%
to my name that I'd scraped
together over the last seven

00:36:48.650 --> 00:36:49.450 align:middle line:90%
or eight years.

00:36:49.450 --> 00:36:53.460 align:middle line:84%
So everything had to be
low tech and low cost.

00:36:53.460 --> 00:36:58.190 align:middle line:84%
So most of the choices
I made are just

00:36:58.190 --> 00:37:00.240 align:middle line:84%
your default
off-the-grid choices.

00:37:00.240 --> 00:37:03.330 align:middle line:10%
It makes sense
conceptually, in a way--

00:37:03.330 --> 00:37:06.950 align:middle line:10%
unless you try to live in
it and then you realize,

00:37:06.950 --> 00:37:08.650 align:middle line:10%
I'm 40 years old.

00:37:08.650 --> 00:37:11.310 align:middle line:84%
I can't run up and down
seven flights of stairs twice

00:37:11.310 --> 00:37:13.755 align:middle line:84%
or three or four times a day
every time I forget a sock

00:37:13.755 --> 00:37:17.160 align:middle line:90%
or whatever.

00:37:17.160 --> 00:37:20.910 align:middle line:84%
A lot of people's
houses are fantasies.

00:37:20.910 --> 00:37:24.150 align:middle line:84%
Everybody's building their
fantasy little dream house.

00:37:24.150 --> 00:37:28.170 align:middle line:84%
And in some ways, I consider
that to be a ridiculous way

00:37:28.170 --> 00:37:29.090 align:middle line:90%
to spend time.

00:37:29.090 --> 00:37:32.580 align:middle line:84%
It's just a distraction
from important things.

00:37:32.580 --> 00:37:37.460 align:middle line:90%


00:37:37.460 --> 00:37:40.876 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:37:40.876 --> 00:37:52.130 align:middle line:90%


00:37:52.130 --> 00:37:54.430 align:middle line:84%
>> It's the same way
as everything else.

00:37:54.430 --> 00:37:57.190 align:middle line:84%
It's not because a house
is big that it's more

00:37:57.190 --> 00:37:59.895 align:middle line:90%
complicated than anything else.

00:37:59.895 --> 00:38:01.270 align:middle line:84%
And it's just one
step at a time.

00:38:01.270 --> 00:38:03.280 align:middle line:84%
You just have to try
and see the big picture

00:38:03.280 --> 00:38:05.900 align:middle line:84%
and then split it
up in little pieces.

00:38:05.900 --> 00:38:10.560 align:middle line:84%
It's not living off-grid
that is the answer.

00:38:10.560 --> 00:38:14.655 align:middle line:84%
And it's not living in an
earthship that's the answer.

00:38:14.655 --> 00:38:18.490 align:middle line:84%
It's a way of thinking
that needs to change.

00:38:18.490 --> 00:38:25.150 align:middle line:84%
Being able to realize
where things come from

00:38:25.150 --> 00:38:26.710 align:middle line:90%
and what they actually cost.

00:38:26.710 --> 00:38:29.490 align:middle line:90%


00:38:29.490 --> 00:38:31.490 align:middle line:10%
>> So there's obviously
no water here right now?

00:38:31.490 --> 00:38:32.290 align:middle line:10%
>> No.

00:38:32.290 --> 00:38:36.380 align:middle line:10%
It comes from way up top
and then through this pipe

00:38:36.380 --> 00:38:38.900 align:middle line:10%
all the way down here--

00:38:38.900 --> 00:38:41.920 align:middle line:10%
a little turbine-- you
might be able to see--

00:38:41.920 --> 00:38:43.970 align:middle line:10%
that the water hits.

00:38:43.970 --> 00:38:46.370 align:middle line:10%
And so it spins and
it makes electricity.

00:38:46.370 --> 00:38:49.430 align:middle line:10%
>> It sounds stupid and it
sounds like I'm being hokey

00:38:49.430 --> 00:38:54.950 align:middle line:10%
and spiritual or
whatever, but you do--

00:38:54.950 --> 00:38:56.420 align:middle line:10%
I had to, anyway.

00:38:56.420 --> 00:38:59.060 align:middle line:84%
You have to figure out where
the water is coming from.

00:38:59.060 --> 00:39:02.480 align:middle line:84%
You have to change
things to suit--

00:39:02.480 --> 00:39:04.220 align:middle line:90%
you see how far the frost goes.

00:39:04.220 --> 00:39:06.440 align:middle line:84%
You see how far the water
goes into the ground when

00:39:06.440 --> 00:39:08.030 align:middle line:90%
it's not moving.

00:39:08.030 --> 00:39:09.530 align:middle line:90%
It's not rocket science.

00:39:09.530 --> 00:39:12.410 align:middle line:84%
Actually, it's more precise
than rocket science.

00:39:12.410 --> 00:39:18.860 align:middle line:90%


00:39:18.860 --> 00:39:21.030 align:middle line:90%
That's all there is to it.

00:39:21.030 --> 00:39:23.180 align:middle line:84%
This disk here,
this flywheel, there

00:39:23.180 --> 00:39:26.780 align:middle line:84%
is very high strength
magnets underneath.

00:39:26.780 --> 00:39:30.285 align:middle line:84%
And as it turns, it
passes by-- there's

00:39:30.285 --> 00:39:31.800 align:middle line:84%
a whole lot of
coils under there.

00:39:31.800 --> 00:39:32.600 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:39:32.600 --> 00:39:33.840 align:middle line:90%
Is it 24 of them?

00:39:33.840 --> 00:39:35.270 align:middle line:90%
I can't remember.

00:39:35.270 --> 00:39:37.940 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, as it spins,
it makes power.

00:39:37.940 --> 00:39:41.590 align:middle line:84%
If there was enough fall,
if there was enough water,

00:39:41.590 --> 00:39:43.890 align:middle line:90%
it could make 500 watts.

00:39:43.890 --> 00:39:47.870 align:middle line:84%
Me, I've only got a
32-foot fall over 300 feet.

00:39:47.870 --> 00:39:50.280 align:middle line:10%
So there is loss in the pipe.

00:39:50.280 --> 00:39:56.330 align:middle line:84%
So when the pond is
up and it's running,

00:39:56.330 --> 00:39:59.960 align:middle line:90%
I would say maybe 90 watts--

00:39:59.960 --> 00:40:01.580 align:middle line:90%
80-90 watts.

00:40:01.580 --> 00:40:06.110 align:middle line:84%
But the good thing about
it is it's 24 hours a day.

00:40:06.110 --> 00:40:10.040 align:middle line:84%
Each of those
panels is 180 watts.

00:40:10.040 --> 00:40:12.680 align:middle line:90%
So there's 360 watts.

00:40:12.680 --> 00:40:14.250 align:middle line:90%
That's ideal.

00:40:14.250 --> 00:40:19.700 align:middle line:90%
So let's say 340 watts really--

00:40:19.700 --> 00:40:22.233 align:middle line:84%
full, direct sunlight,
which is rare.

00:40:22.233 --> 00:40:23.150 align:middle line:90%
When does that happen?

00:40:23.150 --> 00:40:24.576 align:middle line:90%
In the summer.

00:40:24.576 --> 00:40:27.530 align:middle line:84%
>> So basically you've got
about 400 watts worth of PV

00:40:27.530 --> 00:40:28.700 align:middle line:90%
on our old panels.

00:40:28.700 --> 00:40:30.300 align:middle line:90%
And then we added 600 there.

00:40:30.300 --> 00:40:32.450 align:middle line:84%
So that's about 1,000
watts worth of panels.

00:40:32.450 --> 00:40:34.850 align:middle line:10%
So that's 1,000 watts,
or it's a kilowatt.

00:40:34.850 --> 00:40:38.690 align:middle line:10%
So if I get five hours of
sunshine on those panels,

00:40:38.690 --> 00:40:41.240 align:middle line:10%
I end up with five kilowatts--
or five kilowatt hours

00:40:41.240 --> 00:40:42.560 align:middle line:10%
of electricity.

00:40:42.560 --> 00:40:44.874 align:middle line:84%
The average family in
Ontario uses about 35 hours

00:40:44.874 --> 00:40:45.674 align:middle line:90%
of electricity.

00:40:45.674 --> 00:40:50.120 align:middle line:84%
So I can live on five
hours of kilowatt--

00:40:50.120 --> 00:40:52.910 align:middle line:84%
five kilowatt hours if I
shift my thermal or my heat

00:40:52.910 --> 00:40:54.500 align:middle line:90%
loads to propane.

00:40:54.500 --> 00:40:58.100 align:middle line:84%
So what we've done over time
is increased our panels.

00:40:58.100 --> 00:40:59.810 align:middle line:84%
We've added a second
set of solar panels

00:40:59.810 --> 00:41:03.650 align:middle line:84%
in the wind turbine so we can
reduce how much propane we

00:41:03.650 --> 00:41:05.120 align:middle line:90%
have to use.

00:41:05.120 --> 00:41:07.610 align:middle line:84%
But we lived off-grid,
and everybody talks

00:41:07.610 --> 00:41:08.570 align:middle line:90%
about kilowatt hours.

00:41:08.570 --> 00:41:09.990 align:middle line:90%
And I never understood it.

00:41:09.990 --> 00:41:11.170 align:middle line:90%
So I said, until I got--

00:41:11.170 --> 00:41:12.770 align:middle line:90%
I figured this is 1,000 watts.

00:41:12.770 --> 00:41:14.550 align:middle line:84%
I get an hour worth
of sun comes on,

00:41:14.550 --> 00:41:16.580 align:middle line:84%
I get 1 kilowatt
hour of electricity.

00:41:16.580 --> 00:41:18.230 align:middle line:84%
And it all started
making sense to me.

00:41:18.230 --> 00:41:20.425 align:middle line:10%
>> My solar panels are
all up on the roof.

00:41:20.425 --> 00:41:22.070 align:middle line:10%
>> That's so small.

00:41:22.070 --> 00:41:23.570 align:middle line:10%
I was expecting something--

00:41:23.570 --> 00:41:24.723 align:middle line:10%
>> We have more than that.

00:41:24.723 --> 00:41:25.640 align:middle line:10%
There's also another--

00:41:25.640 --> 00:41:26.060 align:middle line:10%
>> Oh.

00:41:26.060 --> 00:41:27.560 align:middle line:90%
>> That's about one kilowatt.

00:41:27.560 --> 00:41:29.930 align:middle line:84%
We have two more kilowatts
right on the roof.

00:41:29.930 --> 00:41:30.895 align:middle line:10%
>> I built this myself.

00:41:30.895 --> 00:41:31.695 align:middle line:10%
I'm very proud.

00:41:31.695 --> 00:41:33.050 align:middle line:10%
>> You built this yourself?

00:41:33.050 --> 00:41:37.430 align:middle line:10%
>> It's my first wind turbine
tower that I ever built.

00:41:37.430 --> 00:41:38.580 align:middle line:90%
Mind you, I had a kit.

00:41:38.580 --> 00:41:40.340 align:middle line:90%
It's a kit, comes from Michigan.

00:41:40.340 --> 00:41:41.570 align:middle line:90%
And it has instructions.

00:41:41.570 --> 00:41:45.020 align:middle line:84%
Its wind tower building
for the complete idiot.

00:41:45.020 --> 00:41:47.645 align:middle line:84%
I need to lower it once
a year because this--

00:41:47.645 --> 00:41:48.617 align:middle line:90%
>> Need to lower--

00:41:48.617 --> 00:41:49.700 align:middle line:90%
>> --wind turbine-- yeah--

00:41:49.700 --> 00:41:51.050 align:middle line:90%
needs to be inspected.

00:41:51.050 --> 00:41:55.035 align:middle line:84%
And it's infinitely
easier to lower the pole

00:41:55.035 --> 00:41:57.410 align:middle line:84%
and look at the generator than
it is to climb up the pole

00:41:57.410 --> 00:42:00.180 align:middle line:90%
and look at the generator.

00:42:00.180 --> 00:42:02.960 align:middle line:10%
>> Or one thing that
does come to mind--

00:42:02.960 --> 00:42:05.780 align:middle line:10%
and we're kind of
proud about it--

00:42:05.780 --> 00:42:08.300 align:middle line:10%
is that we've never
had a power bill.

00:42:08.300 --> 00:42:11.120 align:middle line:10%
We've heard people--
we've heard talk about it.

00:42:11.120 --> 00:42:13.080 align:middle line:84%
We really don't
know what they are.

00:42:13.080 --> 00:42:16.580 align:middle line:84%
>> One of our design factors was
that people coming to visit us

00:42:16.580 --> 00:42:19.010 align:middle line:84%
would not know that
we lived off-grid.

00:42:19.010 --> 00:42:20.630 align:middle line:84%
>> Is this a normal
dishwasher or--

00:42:20.630 --> 00:42:23.180 align:middle line:84%
>> It's an Energy Star
compliant dishwasher.

00:42:23.180 --> 00:42:26.180 align:middle line:84%
And we have choices
to run it low power.

00:42:26.180 --> 00:42:28.190 align:middle line:90%
So its consumption is minimal.

00:42:28.190 --> 00:42:30.150 align:middle line:84%
And we choose when
we want to run it.

00:42:30.150 --> 00:42:34.200 align:middle line:84%
So if we say, it's a good
time to run the dishwasher.

00:42:34.200 --> 00:42:35.000 align:middle line:90%
The sun's out.

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:38.165 align:middle line:90%


00:42:38.165 --> 00:42:44.850 align:middle line:84%
>> We utilize our stuff
as much as we want,

00:42:44.850 --> 00:42:48.360 align:middle line:84%
but there's always an
eye on the battery.

00:42:48.360 --> 00:42:51.720 align:middle line:84%
There's always that thought
in the back of your head,

00:42:51.720 --> 00:42:54.660 align:middle line:90%
are we using too much?

00:42:54.660 --> 00:42:59.107 align:middle line:90%
And what's the weather like?

00:42:59.107 --> 00:42:59.940 align:middle line:90%
What's the weather--

00:42:59.940 --> 00:43:00.900 align:middle line:84%
>> Got a cloudy
stretch coming up--

00:43:00.900 --> 00:43:02.150 align:middle line:90%
>> It looks like we've got a--

00:43:02.150 --> 00:43:03.300 align:middle line:90%
>> --or we-- oh, great.

00:43:03.300 --> 00:43:05.010 align:middle line:90%
We're going to go in the hole.

00:43:05.010 --> 00:43:12.020 align:middle line:84%
>> And I just like to stay fully
charged as much as possible.

00:43:12.020 --> 00:43:14.260 align:middle line:84%
>> This is where the
electricity lives.

00:43:14.260 --> 00:43:21.100 align:middle line:84%
We have a 1,500 amp hour,
a 24 volt battery bank.

00:43:21.100 --> 00:43:24.830 align:middle line:90%
And 2 and 1/2 kilowatt inverter.

00:43:24.830 --> 00:43:25.630 align:middle line:90%
>> OK.

00:43:25.630 --> 00:43:28.960 align:middle line:84%
>> A couple charge controllers,
Maximum Power Point Tracking

00:43:28.960 --> 00:43:30.470 align:middle line:90%
charge controllers.

00:43:30.470 --> 00:43:31.960 align:middle line:90%
This is what's called the MATE.

00:43:31.960 --> 00:43:34.580 align:middle line:90%
It's the brains of the system.

00:43:34.580 --> 00:43:36.290 align:middle line:84%
So right now I just
heard it kick on.

00:43:36.290 --> 00:43:37.540 align:middle line:90%
So something's just turned on.

00:43:37.540 --> 00:43:41.140 align:middle line:84%
So we're now using
1,800 watts of power.

00:43:41.140 --> 00:43:44.140 align:middle line:90%
Batteries are 49.2 volts.

00:43:44.140 --> 00:43:46.840 align:middle line:84%
The output so far today, in
terms of generating power,

00:43:46.840 --> 00:43:49.420 align:middle line:90%
we've generated--

00:43:49.420 --> 00:43:50.390 align:middle line:90%
goes back and forth.

00:43:50.390 --> 00:43:53.020 align:middle line:90%
We've generated-- what was it?

00:43:53.020 --> 00:43:54.160 align:middle line:90%
Nine-- there.

00:43:54.160 --> 00:43:55.780 align:middle line:90%
Nine amps.

00:43:55.780 --> 00:43:56.980 align:middle line:90%
440 watts.

00:43:56.980 --> 00:43:57.850 align:middle line:90%
So not very much.

00:43:57.850 --> 00:44:00.610 align:middle line:84%
Today is a gray day
and there's no wind.

00:44:00.610 --> 00:44:05.200 align:middle line:84%
Right now we're
inverting 1,800 watts.

00:44:05.200 --> 00:44:08.360 align:middle line:84%
So we're using more power
than we're producing.

00:44:08.360 --> 00:44:15.580 align:middle line:84%
I figure the whole
system probably cost

00:44:15.580 --> 00:44:17.365 align:middle line:90%
in the neighborhood of $60,000.

00:44:17.365 --> 00:44:19.490 align:middle line:84%
>> Including the solar
panels and the wind turbine?

00:44:19.490 --> 00:44:22.030 align:middle line:84%
>> Including the solar panels
and the wind turbine, yep.

00:44:22.030 --> 00:44:24.010 align:middle line:84%
>> What would you say is the
percentage of power that you

00:44:24.010 --> 00:44:25.802 align:middle line:84%
get from wind and the
percentage of power--

00:44:25.802 --> 00:44:32.290 align:middle line:84%
>> Oh, we probably get about
10% from wind and about 70% from

00:44:32.290 --> 00:44:35.410 align:middle line:90%
solar and about--

00:44:35.410 --> 00:44:39.300 align:middle line:84%
the other 20% from
our backup generator.

00:44:39.300 --> 00:44:41.100 align:middle line:90%
>> You can use a generator.

00:44:41.100 --> 00:44:43.560 align:middle line:84%
We don't have a
qualm about using it.

00:44:43.560 --> 00:44:48.090 align:middle line:84%
But we are aware that it costs
money to fly the fuel in.

00:44:48.090 --> 00:44:51.360 align:middle line:90%
Fuel costs money by itself.

00:44:51.360 --> 00:44:57.170 align:middle line:84%
And all these gizmos and
gadgets have a lifespan.

00:44:57.170 --> 00:45:00.680 align:middle line:90%
So let's maximize that lifespan.

00:45:00.680 --> 00:45:04.550 align:middle line:84%
If we don't need to fire
up the generator, we won't.

00:45:04.550 --> 00:45:07.120 align:middle line:10%
>> I've met a few people
who live off-the-grid.

00:45:07.120 --> 00:45:08.580 align:middle line:10%
There's one not
too far from here--

00:45:08.580 --> 00:45:11.780 align:middle line:10%
a big system, big, big system.

00:45:11.780 --> 00:45:13.000 align:middle line:10%
Huge system, really.

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:15.470 align:middle line:10%
His whole roof is covered
with solar panels.

00:45:15.470 --> 00:45:17.400 align:middle line:84%
And he should have
all kinds of power.

00:45:17.400 --> 00:45:20.900 align:middle line:84%
But when I went to go see
this huge, wonderful system,

00:45:20.900 --> 00:45:23.090 align:middle line:90%
he couldn't even watch TV.

00:45:23.090 --> 00:45:24.770 align:middle line:90%
Why can't you watch TV?

00:45:24.770 --> 00:45:28.160 align:middle line:84%
Oh, you know, it's
not very sunny today.

00:45:28.160 --> 00:45:30.770 align:middle line:84%
And I don't have
enough electricity.

00:45:30.770 --> 00:45:33.260 align:middle line:90%
Where does it all go?

00:45:33.260 --> 00:45:35.030 align:middle line:84%
He's got a central
heating system,

00:45:35.030 --> 00:45:38.780 align:middle line:84%
and he uses electricity to
run his hot water pumps.

00:45:38.780 --> 00:45:42.200 align:middle line:84%
He's got three hot
water circulating pumps.

00:45:42.200 --> 00:45:45.740 align:middle line:90%
What in the world are you doing?

00:45:45.740 --> 00:45:47.990 align:middle line:84%
And he heats the
water with wood.

00:45:47.990 --> 00:45:51.800 align:middle line:84%
If you had a decent stove in
the basement, a wood furnace

00:45:51.800 --> 00:45:53.690 align:middle line:84%
in the basement,
for crying out loud,

00:45:53.690 --> 00:45:56.090 align:middle line:84%
you could heat your whole
house and your electricity

00:45:56.090 --> 00:45:57.950 align:middle line:90%
could be put to better uses.

00:45:57.950 --> 00:45:59.600 align:middle line:90%
Water pumps?

00:45:59.600 --> 00:46:01.620 align:middle line:90%
Constant hot water?

00:46:01.620 --> 00:46:03.260 align:middle line:90%
Ugh.

00:46:03.260 --> 00:46:07.350 align:middle line:84%
It just-- some people have
the idea, but like you say,

00:46:07.350 --> 00:46:08.150 align:middle line:90%
I'm lucky.

00:46:08.150 --> 00:46:12.650 align:middle line:90%
I can rationalize things.

00:46:12.650 --> 00:46:14.940 align:middle line:90%
>> Our son challenged us a bit--

00:46:14.940 --> 00:46:15.950 align:middle line:90%
quite a bit.

00:46:15.950 --> 00:46:18.445 align:middle line:10%
He went to an outdoor
ed leadership camp

00:46:18.445 --> 00:46:19.570 align:middle line:10%
when he was in high school.

00:46:19.570 --> 00:46:25.438 align:middle line:10%
And when he came back,
his mantra was if it's--

00:46:25.438 --> 00:46:26.480 align:middle line:10%
>> Yellow, let it mellow.

00:46:26.480 --> 00:46:27.605 align:middle line:90%
>> --yellow, let it mellow.

00:46:27.605 --> 00:46:29.105 align:middle line:90%
If it's brown, flush it down.

00:46:29.105 --> 00:46:30.480 align:middle line:84%
>> We have a tank
up on the hill.

00:46:30.480 --> 00:46:31.740 align:middle line:84%
We'll show you
when we go outside.

00:46:31.740 --> 00:46:32.540 align:middle line:90%
>> Oh, OK.

00:46:32.540 --> 00:46:35.760 align:middle line:84%
>> But it's buried
so it doesn't freeze.

00:46:35.760 --> 00:46:41.010 align:middle line:10%
And it's probably level with
the upstairs floor, which

00:46:41.010 --> 00:46:44.568 align:middle line:10%
doesn't really give
enough pressure

00:46:44.568 --> 00:46:46.880 align:middle line:10%
for normal pressure in a house.

00:46:46.880 --> 00:46:50.460 align:middle line:84%
But the less pressure you
have, the less water you use.

00:46:50.460 --> 00:46:52.340 align:middle line:90%
And this is what we do--

00:46:52.340 --> 00:46:53.532 align:middle line:90%
hundred pumps a day.

00:46:53.532 --> 00:46:54.490 align:middle line:90%
>> Hundred pumps a day?

00:46:54.490 --> 00:46:54.960 align:middle line:90%
>> Each.

00:46:54.960 --> 00:46:55.900 align:middle line:90%
>> Each.

00:46:55.900 --> 00:46:58.720 align:middle line:90%


00:46:58.720 --> 00:47:03.500 align:middle line:84%
About like that, and it
comes through the pipe,

00:47:03.500 --> 00:47:06.980 align:middle line:84%
down into big-- it's
an old milk truck tank.

00:47:06.980 --> 00:47:08.934 align:middle line:90%
And that's what feeds the house.

00:47:08.934 --> 00:47:12.810 align:middle line:90%


